		<h3>
			Input Encoding
		</h3>
		<p>
			Without exception, a well-formed <span class="lang">mdoc</span> document consists only of <a class="term"
				href="glossary.xhtml#ascii">ASCII</a> printable characters, the space character, the newline character, and in
			some cases the tab character.  Most modern formatters allow for CR+LF newlines <span class="screen">\r\n</span>, but
			this is not portable.
		</p>
		<p>
			Unilaterally, the backslash <span class="screen">\</span> is always interpreted as the beginning of an <a class="term"
				href="glossary.xhtml#mdoc_escapes">escape sequence</a>.
		</p>
		<p>
			On text input lines (lines not beginning with a <a class="term" href="glossary.xhtml#mdoc_macro">macro</a>), any ASCII
			character may be used and is considered text.
		</p>
		<p>
			On macro lines, however, the following non-alphanumeric characters are syntactically meaningful as follows:
		</p>
		<table width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td>!</td>
				<td>punctuation</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>"</td>
				<td>control character</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>(</td>
				<td>punctuation, control character</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>)</td>
				<td>punctuation</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>,</td>
				<td>punctuation</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>-</td>
				<td>control character</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>.</td>
				<td>punctuation</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>:</td>
				<td>punctuation</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>;</td>
				<td>punctuation</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>?</td>
				<td>punctuation</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>[</td>
				<td>punctuation, control character</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>\</td>
				<td>control character</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>]</td>
				<td>punctuation, control character</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>|</td>
				<td>punctuation</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
